context: After the decline of Aksum, the Eritrean highlands were under the domain of <a0_0>Bahr Negash ruled by <b5_0>the Bahr Negus<b5_0/><a0_0/>. The area was then known as <b6_0>Ma'ikele Bahr<b6_0/> ("between the seas/rivers," i.e. the land between the Red Sea and the Mereb river). It was later renamed under <b9_0>Emperor Zara Yaqob<b9_0/> as the domain of the Bahr Negash, the <a1_0>Medri Bahri<a1_0/> ("<a4_0>Sea land<a4_0/>" in Tingrinya, although it included some areas like Shire on the other side of the Mereb, today in Ethiopia). With its capital at <a2_0><b8_0>Debarwa<b8_0/><a2_0/>, the state's main provinces were <a3_0><b7_0>Hamasien<b7_0/>, Serae and Akele Guzai<a3_0/>.
